The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, January 29, 2004 				 Cutting edge for export products 
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Jan. 28: India Inc has welcomed the mini exim policy saying it would enhance the export competitiveness of Indian products.																								The exim policy initiatives will enhance Indias long-term export competitiveness said Yogendra Modi, president of the Federation of Indian Chamber of Commerce and Industry.																								The digital signature and electronic fund transfer will cut transaction costs and time for exporters and establish India as a world class export base. 																								CII president Anand Mahindra said, The exim facilitation measures will boost the service sector. Steps were aimed at reducing the transaction cost and also bring in transparency.																								While welcoming the enhancement of equity base of ECGC and proposed creation of National Export Insurance Account (NEIA), Modi requested the government to work out necessary modalities to enable projects valued at more that $1 billion to be underwritten.																								Industry associations lauded the move allowing duty free imports of fuel under the DFRC scheme. 																								PHDCCI president Ravi Wig said, We are hopeful that after the electoral process is completed, comprehensive policy measures and simplification of procedures will be announced.																								Rafeeque Ahmed, president, Federation of Indian Export Organisations (FIEO), welcomed measures like the gold card scheme for the exporters with proven track record for availability of export credit. Allowing free import of gold and silver will give boost to jewellery exports, he added. 
